<div id="review_613376173" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/613376173" />
    <a title="Lewis Weinstein" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2231715-lewis-weinstein"><img alt="Lewis Weinstein" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442501879p2/2231715.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/613376173?book_show_action=true">May 12, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lewis Weinstein" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lewis Weinstein" href="/user/show/2231715-lewis-weinstein">Lewis Weinstein</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2231715-lewis-weinstein?shelf=crime-and-thrillers">crime-and-thrillers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer613376173" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer96820465586504356">Many detective stories start out with a bang. Something dramatic happens. &quot;Knots and Crosses,&quot; Rankin&apos;s first Rebus novel, and maybe his first novel altogether, is not that way. After 50+ pages, still not much had happened.<br/><br/>Most detective novels alternate scenes of tension and scenes of relief. Not this one. When the tension finally starts to build, it continues on an unrelenting screaming frightening path to the end of the story.<br/><br/>I guess you can tell I enjoyed the read. That&apos;s all I&apos;m going to sa</span>
  <span id="freeText96820465586504356" style="display:none">Many detective stories start out with a bang. Something dramatic happens. "Knots and Crosses," Rankin's first Rebus novel, and maybe his first novel altogether, is not that way. After 50+ pages, still not much had happened.<br /><br />Most detective novels alternate scenes of tension and scenes of relief. Not this one. When the tension finally starts to build, it continues on an unrelenting screaming frightening path to the end of the story.<br /><br />I guess you can tell I enjoyed the read. That's all I'm going to say since I don't want to reveal the plot. </span>
  <a data-text-id="96820465586504356" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
